            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the double-slit interference calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool models Young’s double-slit experiment with
                monochromatic, coherent light. Given the wavelength \( \lambda
                \), slit separation \( d \), and screen distance \( L \), it
                computes:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Fringe spacing \( \Delta y \) on the screen</li>
                <li>Position and angle of a chosen bright or dark fringe</li>
                <li>Path difference between the two slits</li>
                <li>An idealized interference intensity pattern</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Key formulas for double-slit interference</h3>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  1. Condition for bright fringes (maxima)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ d \sin\theta = m\lambda \quad (m = 0, \pm 1, \pm 2, \dots)
                  \]
                </p>
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1 mt-3">
                  2. Condition for dark fringes (minima)
                </p>
                <p>\[ d \sin\theta = \left(m + \tfrac{1}{2}\right)\lambda \]</p>
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1 mt-3">
                  3. Small-angle approximation
                </p>
                <p>
                  For small angles, \( \sin\theta \approx \tan\theta \approx
                  \theta \) (in radians), and \[ \tan\theta \approx \frac{y}{L}
                  \quad \Rightarrow \quad \theta \approx \frac{y}{L}. \]
                </p>
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1 mt-3">
                  4. Fringe position on the screen
                </p>
                <p>
                  Combining the above for bright fringes: \[ y_m \approx
                  \frac{m\lambda L}{d} \] and for dark fringes: \[ y_m \approx
                  \frac{\left(m + \tfrac{1}{2}\right)\lambda L}{d}. \]
                </p>
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1 mt-3">5. Fringe spacing</p>
                <p>
                  The distance between adjacent bright fringes is \[ \Delta y
                  \approx \frac{\lambda L}{d}. \]
                </p>
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1 mt-3">6. Path difference</p>
                <p>
                  The path difference between the two slits is \[ \Delta = d
                  \sin\theta \approx d \frac{y}{L}. \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Worked example</h3>
              <p>Suppose you use:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  \( \lambda = 632.8\ \text{nm} = 6.328\times10^{-7}\ \text{m}
                  \)
                </li>
                <li>\( d = 0.25\ \text{mm} = 2.5\times10^{-4}\ \text{m} \)</li>
                <li>\( L = 1.5\ \text{m} \)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Then the fringe spacing is</p>
              <p>
                \[ \Delta y = \frac{\lambda L}{d} =
                \frac{6.328\times10^{-7}\times 1.5}{2.5\times10^{-4}} \approx
                3.8\times10^{-3}\ \text{m} = 3.8\ \text{mm}. \]
              </p>
              <p>
                The first bright fringe (\(m = 1\)) appears at \( y_1 \approx
                3.8\ \text{mm} \) above and below the center.
              </p>

              <h2>Assumptions and limitations</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>Monochromatic, coherent light source (e.g., laser).</li>
                <li>
                  Slits are narrow compared to the wavelength and separation.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Screen is far enough that the small-angle approximation holds.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Single-slit diffraction envelope is not included; this is a
                  pure two-slit model.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Tips for lab use</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Measure several fringe spacings and average them to reduce
                  measurement error.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use the calculator in reverse: if you know \( \Delta y \), \(
                  L \), and \( d \), you can solve for \( \lambda \).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Keep the room dark and use a narrow slit before the double
                  slit to improve coherence.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-10">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">
                Double-slit interference FAQ
              </h2>
              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-container">
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What is double-slit interference?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Double-slit interference occurs when light from two narrow,
                    closely spaced slits overlaps on a screen. The waves from
                    each slit combine, producing bright fringes where they
                    interfere constructively and dark fringes where they
                    interfere destructively.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How do I choose the slit separation and screen distance?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    For a visible, well-spaced pattern, you want the fringe
                    spacing \( \Delta y = \lambda L / d \) to be a few
                    millimeters. If fringes are too close, decrease \( d \) or
                    increase \( L \); if they are too far apart, increase \( d
                    \) or decrease \( L \).
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Why are there both bright and dark fringes?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    At some points on the screen, the waves from the two slits
                    arrive in phase (path difference is an integer multiple of
                    the wavelength), giving constructive interference and bright
                    fringes. At other points, they arrive out of phase by half a
                    wavelength, giving destructive interference and dark
                    fringes.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Does this calculator include quantum effects?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    The calculator uses the standard wave-optics model
                    (classical interference). It does not simulate single-photon
                    detection or which-path measurements, but the same fringe
                    positions apply in the quantum picture when no which-path
                    information is available.
                  </p>
                </details>
              </div>
            </section>
